{{Infobox Historic building |name=Palácio de Ferro |image= Palácio de Ferro.jpg |caption= Palácio de Ferro circa 2011 |map_type= |latitude= |longitude= |location_town=[[Luanda]] |location_country=[[Angola]] |architect= |client= |engineer= |construction_start_date=1890s |date_demolished= |cost= |structural_system= |style= |size= }}
'''Palácio de Ferro''' ({{lang-en|Iron Palace}}) is a historical building in the [[Angola]]n capital [[Luanda]], ''believed to have been designed and built by &ndash; or by someone associated with &ndash; [[Gustave Eiffel]]'', builder of the world-famous icons, the [[Eiffel Tower]] in Paris and the [[Statue of Liberty]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20090122-luanda-breathes-new-life-once-rusty-iron-palace|date=2009-01-22 |author= Louisse Redvers|title=Luanda breathes new life into once-rusty Iron Palace|publisher=France 24 |accessdate=2009-01-23 }} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>
The history of the structure is shrouded in mystery since no official record of it exists. It is believed to have been pre-built in the 1890s in France and was destined to be placed in [[Madagascar]] via boat. Instead, the building ended-up in [[Angola]]'s [[Skeleton Coast]] after the ship carrying it was drifted by the notorious [[Benguela]] currents. [[Portuguese empire|Portuguese rulers]] of the colony then claimed the ship along with all its contents, including the palace.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blnz.com/news/2009/01/22/Luanda_breathes_life_into_once-rusty_9775.html|date=2009-01-21 |title=Luanda breathes new life into once-rusty Iron Palace|publisher=BLNZ |accessdate=2009-01-23 }}</ref>
During the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] era, the building had a great deal of prestige and it was used as an art center. But after the [[Angolan War of Independence|independence of Angola]], the palace was left in neglect with its surrounding area eventually ending up as a [[parking lot]]. It was also heavily damaged during the [[Angolan Civil War]] leaving some of its structures in a rusted and rotting condition.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.info7.com.mx/noticia.php?id=75584&secc=7|date=2009-01-21 |title=Brasileños restauraron 'Palacio de Hierro' de Angola, con diseño de Eiffel|publisher=Info7 |accessdate=2009-01-23 }} ([[Spanish language|Spanish]])</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/PopArte/0,,MUL962028-7084,00-BRASILEIROS+RESTAURAM+PALACIO+DE+FERRO+DE+ANGOLA.html|date=2009-01-19 |title=Brasileiros restauram "Palácio de Ferro" de Angola |publisher=Globo.com |accessdate=2009-01-23 }}([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]])</ref>
Currently, the building is undergoing a renovation funded by profits from Angola's [[oil]] boom with the help of Brazilian construction companies, as many of the reclaimed iron balustrades and floor tiles were individually renovated in [[Rio de Janeiro]]. It now stands as the symbol of the city's rebirth as well as a point of social reference for the future. The [[Ministry of Culture (Angola)|Ministry of Culture of Angola]] is still deciding whether the building is to become a [[diamond]] museum or a restaurant.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ph.news.yahoo.com/afp/20090122/tls-angola-architecture-france-brazil-aeafa1b.html |date=2009-01-23 |title=Luanda breathes new life into once-rusty Iron Palace |publisher=Yahoo! News |accessdate=2009-01-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131235620/http://ph.news.yahoo.com/afp/20090122/tls-angola-architecture-france-brazil-aeafa1b.html |archivedate=2009-01-31 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angolaemb.se/informacao/press/press-6/n10.htm |date=July 2007 |title=Culture Ministry and Endiama Sign Contract for Iron Palace Restoration |publisher=Embassy of Republic of Angola |accessdate=2009-01-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090929233208/http://www.angolaemb.se/informacao/press/press-6/n10.htm |archivedate=2009-09-29 |df= }}</ref>
