The consonants {{IPA|/b d̪ g/}} often weaken to {{IPA|[β ð ɣ]}} intervocalically.<ref name="s8">{{Harvcoltxt|Saeed|1999|p=8}}</ref> The retroflex plosive {{IPA|/ɖ/}} may have an implosive quality for some speakers, and intervocalically it can be realized as the flap {{IPA|[ɽ]}}.<ref name="s8" /> Some speakers produce {{IPA|/ħ/}} with [[epiglottal trill]]ing.<ref name="g14">{{Harvcoltxt|Gabbard|2010|p=14}}</ref> {{IPA|/q/}} is often [[epiglottal]]ized.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Edmondson|Esling|Harris|n.d.|p=5}}</ref>

The language has five basic [[vowel]]s. Each has a front and back variation as well as long or short versions. This gives a distinct 20 pure vowel sounds. It also exhibits three tones: high, low and falling. Vowels harmonize within a harmonic group, so all vowels within the group must either be front or back. The Somali orthography does not distinguish between the front and back variants of vowels, however, as there are few minimal pairs.<ref>http://www.ling.upenn.edu/courses/Spring_1998/ling202/atr.html</ref>

The syllable structure of Somali is (C)V(C). Root [[morpheme]]s usually have a mono- or di-syllabic structure.

Pitch is phonemic in Somali, but it is debated whether Somali is a [[pitch accent]] or [[tonal language|tonal]] language.<ref name="Ceolotw">{{cite book|last=Keith Brown|first=Sarah Ogilvie|title=Concise Encyclopedia of Languages of the World|year=2010|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=0080877753|page=987|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F2SRqDzB50wC}}</ref> Andrzejewski (1954) posits that Somali is a tonal language,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Andrzejewski|first1=Bogumit Witalis|title="Is Somali a Tone-language?", Proceedings of the Twenty-Third International Congress of Orientalists|date=1954|publisher=Royal Asiatic Society|pages=367–368|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/proceedings-of-the-twenty-third-international-congress-of-orientalists-texte-imprime-cambridge-21st-28th-august-1954/oclc/496050266|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref> whereas Banti (1988) suggests that it is a pitch accent language.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Banti|first1=Giorgio|title="Two Cushitic Systems: Somali and Oromo nouns", Autosegmental Studies on Pitch Accent|date=1988|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=3110874261|pages=11–50|url=http://www.ddl.ish-lyon.cnrs.fr/colloques/3L_2008/3LCourseMaterial/African%20(Cushitic)%20topics%20-%20M.%20Mous/cushTone/Banti%20Two%20Cushitic%20systems.pdf|accessdate=26 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011132347/http://www.ddl.ish-lyon.cnrs.fr/colloques/3L_2008/3LCourseMaterial/African%20(Cushitic)%20topics%20-%20M.%20Mous/cushTone/Banti%20Two%20Cushitic%20systems.pdf|archive-date=11 October 2017|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

